        10/18/2015
    

Carl's Jr. Is located near the intersection of highway 15 and route 127.  Highway 15 is a major thoroughfare that takes you from Barstow to Lost Wages.  Route 127 is a less-traveled backroads highway that takes you to the southern and eastern entrances of Death Valley National Park.  I have visited Death Valley National Park on six different weekends, in the years 2013-2014, and found Carl's Jr. to be a welcome pit stop after a long day of hiking and photography.   I always order the Carl's Jr. Santa Fe chicken sandwich, and typically I always pay extra for additional roasted green chiles.  Because of the energy-draining quality of hiking and doing photography for eight straight hours, and because of their delicious nature, I sometimes order TWO Santa Fe chicken sandwiches.  Mmmm, I do like them. Carl's Jr. In Baker, CA is clean, and has polite and service-oriented cashiers.  I am also glad that Carl's Jr. In Baker, CA has good cell phone reception, since I like to call my better half after completing my long day of exploring and hiking.  After my weekend desert photography weekends, I have also gone to Carl's Jr. in Ridgecrest, CA and in Joshua Tree, CA, and always order Santa Fe chicken, with extra roasted green chiles.  THE MAD GREEK.  An alternative to Carl's Jr. in Baker, CA is The Mad Greek.  The Mad Greek is also located at the same intersection of Route 15 and Route 127, but I think that one visit to The Mad Greek is enough.   The Mad Greek is distinguished by its amusing tacky decor (plenty of faux Greek statues), but the cuisine is not perfect (the dolmas are soggy).  And so, I tend to opt for Carl's Jr. when returning home from Death Valley, but once I stopped in Barstow at a Subway restaurant.CARL'S JR. COFFEE.   Also, the coffee at Carl's Jr. is good.  The coffee is MUCH BETTER than that from Starbucks (blech, yech, ewww) but not as good as the coffee from Peet's.  Good coffee is important, because it takes me six hours of driving at night to return home, and generally I'm on the road until nearly midnight after my long days in the desert.




